{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17413399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17413399"},"attributes":{"position":17,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T08:10:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T08:10:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"901"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472026","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472026"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:54:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:54:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"901"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261100"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:52:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:28:52+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":62,"questionsAnswered":61,"marksTotal":61,"marksAttainable":61,"marksAttempted":61,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T09:15:31+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.2,"questionsCorrect":12,"marksCorrect":12},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"901","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/901"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.5,0.16,0.15,0.05,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"901"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104251"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"901","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/901"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"901"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86588"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"147"},{"type":"tags","id":"1142"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25966"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42173"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43048"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44038"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104251","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104251"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 10-year-old boy is brought to the Emergency Department by his parents. He has a history of asthma, for which he takes a regular preventer and as-needed reliever. Since developing an upper respiratory tract infection in the last three days, his asthma has worsened. On examination, he can speak a few words in one breath, is sitting up, hunched forward, and is alert and not cyanosed. His pulse rate is 130/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min and SpO2 91% on room air. There is widespread wheeze on auscultation of his chest. In hospital, he receives nebulised salbutamol and oral corticosteroids after which he improves rapidly.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate follow-up approach?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["GP review within 72 hours","GP review in one week","Respiratory outpatient review in 48 hours","Respiratory outpatient review in one week","GP review if he does not continue to improve, or deteriorates"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe Australian Asthma Handbook and National Asthma Council Australia guidelines emphasise the importance of early follow-up after an acute asthma exacerbation requiring emergency care. \u003Cstrong\u003EGP review within 72 hours\u003C/strong\u003E is recommended as the standard of care. This allows for assessment of recovery, review of medication technique, and adjustment of the asthma action plan.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGP review in one week\u003C/strong\u003E is too late, as the critical period for preventing relapse is in the first few days after discharge. The first 48-72 hours after discharge represent a vulnerable period where symptoms may recur.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERespiratory outpatient review in 48 hours\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely necessary for uncomplicated asthma exacerbations that respond well to initial treatment. Non-GP Specialist review should be reserved for cases of difficult-to-control asthma or frequent exacerbations and it is important to remember that GP\u0027s are specialists with adequate training to manage mild-moderate asthma. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERespiratory outpatient review in one week\u003C/strong\u003E is not the preferred option as the GP should coordinate initial and ongoing post-discharge care. Non-GP Specialist review may be indicated down the track if he has recurrent exacerbation that do not respond to escalating preventative therapies. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGP review if he does not continue to improve\u003C/strong\u003E is inadequate as it places the onus on the family to determine clinical deterioration. A planned review is essential to ensure appropriate follow-up occurs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe post-discharge plan should also include provision of an interim written asthma action plan, education about medications (including technique), and arrangements for a second GP review within 2-4 weeks to optimise ongoing management. This approach is supported by both the Australian Asthma Handbook and the Global Initiative for Asthma (GINA) guidelines.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Clinical review with the patient\u0027s GP is recommended within 2-3 days after discharge from hospital for an acute asthma exacerbation.","Post-discharge care should include an interim written asthma action plan and education about medications.","A second GP review should occur within 2-4 weeks to optimise ongoing management."],"references":["National Asthma Council, Providing post-acute care, Australian Asthma Handbook, accessed April 2020,\u00a0https://www.asthmahandbook.org.au/acute-asthma/clinical/post-acute-care"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86588"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"901"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86588","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86588"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-30T09:53:26+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-30T09:53:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"901"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104251"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms"